Press Release<br /><!-- NewsDate.start -->April 3, 2006<!-- NewsDate.end --><p style="text-align: center">
<span class="PRTitle"><!-- NewsTitle.start -->DILG HAS NO CONTROL OVER LOCAL 
GOVERNMENTS; 
<br />IT SHOULD NOW BE ABOLISHED -- PIMENTEL<!-- NewsTitle.end --></span></p>
<!-- NewsBody.start --><p>Senate Minority Leader Aquilino Nene Q. Pimentel, 
Jr. (PDP-Laban) today accused the Department of Interior and Local Government 
(DILG) of stepping beyond the bounds of its legal functions by using the Local 
Government Units (LGUs) for the signature campaign for Charter Change based on 
the mistaken notion that they are under the control of the department.</p>
<p>Pimentel said the DILG under Secretary Ronaldo Puno, has no business acting 
like an overload of the LGUs and dictating on them what they should do because 
they have become autonomous entities since the enactment of the Local Government 
Code in 1991.</p>
<p>The actuations of Secretary Puno violate local autonomy because the Local 
Government Code has removed the LGUs  provinces, cities, municipalities and 
barangays  from the control of the DILG.</p>
<p>In fact, he said one the logical consequences of the enactment of the Code is 
the abolition of the DILG.</p>
<p>The DILG should have been phased out five years after the enactment of the 
Local Government Code, said Pimentel, principal author of the Code.</p>
<p>Pimentel said the DILGs denial that it was behind the Cha-Cha signature 
drive falls flat in the face of reports that the DILG field offices in the 
provinces, cities and municipalities were the ones that distributed the Cha-Cha 
forms during the March 25 barangay assemblies.</p>
<p>He said he also received reports that the DILG distributed P500,000 to each 
congressional district for the signature drive and the money was coursed through 
the Automated Teller Machines (ATM) accounts of the departments regional 
coordinators.</p>
<p>Aside from this, Pimentel said the DILG was also involved in the printing of 
the forms for which public funds were spent.</p>
<p>The DILG masterminded the printing of the forms which were found to be 
similar throughout the nation. There was only one source for the forms and 
public money was used for it, he said.</p>
<p>Saying that what the DILG is doing is against the law, Pimentel said this 
probably explains why Puno, being the master operator that he is, has 
delegated to DILG Undersecretary Wencelito Andanar the signing of directives 
related to the peoples initiative for Charter Change.</p>
<p>You will not see the signature of Secretary Puno in the DILG directives. 
Only the name and signature of Undersecretary Andanar can be found there.</p>
